Short opening hook. Usually one line. Slightly provocative or observational.
Feels like a text message, not a “LinkedIn post.”
Minimal adjectives. No motivational fluff.
Uses real numbers, outcomes, screenshots, or proof.
Focus on what happened, not “journey” storytelling.
Sentences are short. Often single-line paragraphs.
Slightly blunt tone. Confident but not polished-corporate.
Doesn’t over-explain context. Assumes reader can infer.
Mix of casual + technical naturally.
Uses contrast well: “People think X. Reality is Y.”
Often ends with a simple observation instead of a CTA.
No emojis or very minimal.
Avoids buzzwords like “thrilled”, “excited”, “grateful”.
Feels written fast, but intentionally sharp.
Prioritizes distribution-worthy lines people repost/reply to.
Screenshots/images do heavy lifting instead of long explanations.
Makes niche internet/dev/startup culture references naturally.
Slight edge/savagery in phrasing without sounding cringe.
Structure is usually: hook → proof/context → sharp takeaway.
Reads like someone building in public, not personal branding.
